Step two, you don't deface or mark an American Flag or display it with any kind of marking.  Step three you don't sell any form of merchandise (and basically any other form of 'thing) using an American flag or use it in advertising. Bet you he bought that flag from somewhere.  Step four, the flag shouldn't touch the ground (Or any other thing below it) under any circumstance while being carried or displayed. (Which, kneeling is against the unenforceable flag code, which would mean he follows that standard for other people but not himself.) Â @tabethapacion7137Â  America was nuts long before Trump and it will be, long after. I think it's mostly due to two factors. It's a relatively young country and the cold war really messed with their shared perceptions. A large portion of the population rejects any form of socialism at face value because "communism bad", not understanding that left-wing vs right-wing is a delicate balance and swinging too far either way breaks a country.   No matter what economic system we operate under, absolute wealth equality is infeasible. So there will always be people who are richer  than others and people who are poorer than others. Their interests clash due to the variations in their circumstances. That is what left-wing vs right-wing is really about. If you say "fuck the rich" and go full left-wing they'll take their wealth and invest it somewhere else. If you say "fuck the poor" and go full right-wing, you get lots of crime and lots of civil unrest.   A stable country is one where there is willing compromise between the two. A democracy is a country that values each citizen equally. That's why they all get a vote, and why (not in the US with their electoral college) all votes are worth the same. So in a democracy, the left/right balance is decided by wealth disparity and average wealth. People vote on which policies will benefit them. So poor people tend to vote socialist, rich people tend to vote capitalist and middle class flip flops depending on "which side is going too far".   But in the US, they had a huge crackdown on communism in the country throughout the cold war. So people who believed that the prosperity of a country is measured by how they treat those worst off were basically considered traitors. That became part of the cultural identity of the country and that's why they don't embrace socialist ideas like "state-run healthcare", "labour unions" and even the extreme basics like food banks and homeless shelters (social services that have existed for millenia) are contested water.

These are funny, but lets not ignore the fact that this method of reporting can be somewhat disingenuous and can take advantage of people's psychology to some extent. One of the aspects of social psychology is agreeability, so when you present to someone a loaded question in a joking way, they are likely to make an easy agreeable response, even if that response is intolerant. Make no mistake: I believe that people are to be held accountable for everything they say, and I acknowledge that what we see here is not the reporter's fault. Racism and intolerance are real. So is stupidity. We can see it clearly. BUT this is a prime example of judging people by the surface. take the latest BORAT movie for example. He'll say something totally disgusting and intolerant and then blame people for agreeing with him, or singing along with his ridiculous songs. He depicts the people who don't call him out as part of the problem, and then makes a movie of all the worst clips to make a political party look like it is ALL idiots. This is divisive. Let's be clear that much of what we see in these people is not correct, but I can assure you that this stupidity exists on both sides of the political spectrum. People have different priorities and need to find a way to meet in the middle. Conservative vs progressive is always a war. Both sides need to hear eachother out completely. Watch eachothers news networks to see the REAL FUEL OF THE FIRE. Look at eachother's facts. Consider eachother's fears and help them understand why they don't have to be afraid. What I think you will find, though, is that we all have valid fears and your own feelings won't alleviate them without an education of what both sides believe, straight from the source. Be quick to listen, slow to speak and slow to anger. Tolerate eachother's questions. There is only one truth.. Both sides have their fair share of lies, but you would never believe me unless you identify with truth instead of your favorite color. The psychology tricks and emotional manipulation of the media have stained our minds and hearts, and you know its true when both sides have some valid points to make, but never get anywhere with eachother because they don't truly listen to eachother. At the end of the day, we are all missing the big picture. Step back from the politics and learn about economics, philosophy, sociology, history of the entire world, cultures, theology, political sciences, corruption, the law, and other people's perspectives. Then revisit the politics.

Â @spol1622Â  You can certainly make that argument, and you wouldn't be alone. All tests measure the ability to take that specific test and answer those specific questions. Take a driving test, for example. Let's say I took it in California in a Prius. I get 100/100. This certainly does not display my full driving characteristics or even likelihood of getting into an accident. It just means I knew how to do well on the test. It is, however "a measure" of your driving ability, assuming that you're motivated to do your best. So, while we certainly cannot say IQ tests are the measure of absolute intelligence with 100% accuracy, we CAN say they are "a measure" of IQ for the majority of people. So, you can have a very high IQ and do poorly at school or a relatively low IQ and do well in school. Most of the things we learn in school are not hard concepts. It's memorization. Even upper division science classes in college are not incredibly demanding of high intelligence. That's more volume. Intelligence itself is fairly abstract. All that being said, I'm not getting into a car with someone that doesn't have a license bc they failed the test.
